[Rotavirus is a virus that causes gastroenteritis. Rotavirus disease causes severe watery diarrhea, often with vomiting, fever, and abdominal pain. In babies and young children, it can lead to dehydration and rotavirus infection is the leading cause of severe diarrhea in infants and young children worldwide. Globally, it causes more than a half a million deaths each year in children younger than 5 years of age.

The outbreak in Laurinburg is atypical in that it is localised and that adults seem to be affected as well as children (although this is difficult to assess in the absence of case numbers). Rotavirus spreads easily among young children. Children can spread the virus both before and after they become sick with diarrhea. They can also pass rotavirus to family members and other people with whom they have close contact.

Effective vaccines are now available . A summarised account of the development of rotavirus vaccines and their deployment in practice can be accessed at the WHO web-site: http://www.who.int/nuvi/rotavirus/en/.

A map showing the location of Laurinburg in North Carolina can be accessed at:http://www.laurinburg.org/about/default.aspx. - Mod.CP]
